<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF67D7EDA648A9FA" blockId="3.[189,334,433,459]" box="[189,334,433,459]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading id="082A2C15FF9FFFB3FF67D7EDA648A9FA" bold="true" box="[189,334,433,459]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FF67D7EDA648A9FA" bold="true" box="[189,334,433,459]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF30D783A62CA9C8" blockId="3.[189,755,479,539]" box="[234,298,479,505]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FF30D783A62CA9C8" bold="true" box="[234,298,479,505]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF67D45DA5F5AA2A" blockId="3.[189,755,479,539]" box="[189,755,513,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
LENGTH. Body 
<quantity id="9425369CFF9FFFB3FEA9D45DA517AA2A" box="[371,529,513,539]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.055" metricValueMax="1.14" metricValueMin="0.97" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="10.55" valueMax="11.4" valueMin="9.7">9.7–11.4 mm</quantity>
, wing 
<quantity id="9425369CFF9FFFB3FD84D45DA5E8AA2A" box="[606,750,513,539]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.75" metricValueMax="9.3" metricValueMin="8.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="8.75" valueMax="9.3" valueMin="8.2">8.2–9.3 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF67D41DA5E5AB34" blockId="3.[189,1399,577,773]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
HEAD. Facial shape simple, in lateral view, almost straight, without central knob and without antennal tubercle; oral cavity round, smooth without notch; clypeus horse-shoe shaped; face black, black pilose; frons black, black pilose with two small white pollinose maculae laterally along eye margin (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF9FFFB3FAD1D4D9A261AAAE" box="[1291,1383,645,671]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1896,1922]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov. A. Habitus, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). B. Habitus, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). C. Head, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). D. Antenna, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). E. Metaleg, frontal view, paratype ♂ (JSA). Scale bars: A–C, E = 1.0 mm; D = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954990" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954990/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 1 
<collectionCode id="35CC03BCFF9FFFB3FA94D4D9A261AAAE" box="[1358,1383,645,671]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">C</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
); vertical triangle black, black pilose; eye pilose; postocular orbit dorsally broad; eye-contiguity relatively short, about a quarter as long as length of vertical triangle; antenna (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF9FFFB3FC30D495A343AAD2" box="[1002,1093,713,739]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1896,1922]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov. A. Habitus, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). B. Habitus, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). C. Head, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). D. Antenna, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). E. Metaleg, frontal view, paratype ♂ (JSA). Scale bars: A–C, E = 1.0 mm; D = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954990" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954990/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 1 
<collectionCode id="35CC03BCFF9FFFB3FBF6D495A343AAD2" box="[1068,1093,713,739]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">D</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
) orange-brown, elongate, basoflagellomere four times longer than broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF67D570A4C9ABBA" blockId="3.[189,1398,811,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
THORAX. Black, extensively pilose; postpronotum pilose; katepisternum almost entirely pilose, only narrowly bare antero-dorsally and medially along posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF9FFFB3FBD0D512A36BAB59" box="[1034,1133,846,872]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[189,232,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,798,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[189,1398,798,1784]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Pilosity of the katepisternum, ventro-lateral view. A. Scaeva pyrastri (Linnaeus, 1758), ♂ (JSA), Switzerland, with extensive pilosity. B. Psilota atra (Fallén, 1817), ♂ (JSA), the Netherlands, with extensive pilosity. C. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov., paratype ♂ (JSA), with extensive pilosity. D. Trichopsomyia joratensis Goeldlin, 1997, ♀ (JSA), Belgium, with separated dorsal and ventral pile patch. Scale bars = 0.5 mm. a = ventral pile patch; b = antero-dorsal area; c = postero-medial margin; d = dorsal pile patch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954994" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954994/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 3 
<collectionCode id="35CC03BCFF9FFFB3FB8CD512A36BAB59" box="[1110,1133,846,872]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">C</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
); katepimeron pilose; metasternum rather well developed with some pile medio-laterally.
</paragraph>
<caption id="07A2CBF1FF9FFFB3FF67D134A493AFDC" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954990" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3954990" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954990/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" startId="3.[189,232,1896,1922]" targetBox="[189,1398,955,1854]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="53629B79FF9FFFB3FF67D134A493AFDC" blockId="3.[189,1399,1896,2029]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FF67D134A609AFB3" bold="true" box="[189,271,1896,1922]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="94DDE0FAFF9FFFB3FEC1D134A51BAFB3" authority="Steenis &amp; Wyatt, 2020" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Wyatt" authorityYear="2020" box="[283,541,1896,1922]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Trichopsomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FEC1D134A51BAFB3" box="[283,541,1896,1922]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trichopsomyia pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="7A9AFA10FF9FFFB3FDF2D135A581AFB2" box="[552,647,1897,1923]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FD49D134A5AEAFB3" bold="true" box="[659,680,1896,1922]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A</emphasis>
. Habitus, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FF67D1D0A7D7AF97" bold="true" box="[189,209,1932,1958]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">B</emphasis>
. Habitus, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FCA2D1D0A48BAF97" bold="true" box="[888,909,1932,1958]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">C</emphasis>
. Head, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FE87D1F3A674AFF8" bold="true" box="[349,370,1967,1993]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">D</emphasis>
. Antenna, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF9FFFB3FB92D1F3A35AAFF8" bold="true" box="[1096,1116,1967,1993]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">E</emphasis>
. Metaleg, frontal view, paratype ♂ (JSA). Scale bars: A–C, E = 1.0 mm; D = 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D750A3BEA95D" blockId="4.[189,1399,267,370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
WING. Membrane entirely brownish infuscated (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF98FFB4FD23D757A43DA917" box="[761,827,267,294]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1896,1922]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov. A. Habitus, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). B. Habitus, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). C. Head, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). D. Antenna, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). E. Metaleg, frontal view, paratype ♂ (JSA). Scale bars: A–C, E = 1.0 mm; D = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954990" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A–B) covered with unusually long microtrichia, except bare on basal ¹⁄10 of cell bm; cell c exceptionally wide, clearly wider than cell bm; vein dm-cu ending almost perpendicularly to vein M; vein M 
<subScript id="CF59993CFF98FFB4FD25D738A40EA943" attach="left" box="[767,776,356,370]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">1</subScript>
ending strongly oblique at vein R 
<subScript id="CF59993CFF98FFB4FB4CD738A3B7A943" attach="left" box="[1174,1201,356,370]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4+5</subScript>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D7CFA4F0AA26" blockId="4.[189,1398,403,535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
LEGS. Black, except apical half of basitarsi, and tarsomeres 2–4 white; pile long and predominantly black, but white parts of tarsi with long white pile; metaleg (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF98FFB4FC50D7EAA4E4A9E0" box="[906,994,438,465]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1896,1922]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,955,1854]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov. A. Habitus, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). B. Habitus, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). C. Head, dorsal view, paratype ♂ (NHMUK 010864266). D. Antenna, lateral view, holotype ♂ (NHMUK 010864268). E. Metaleg, frontal view, paratype ♂ (JSA). Scale bars: A–C, E = 1.0 mm; D = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954990" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954990/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Fig. 1 
<collectionCode id="35CC03BCFF98FFB4FC16D7EBA4E4A9E0" box="[972,994,439,465]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
) with femur narrow and elongate, but slightly thickened and more densely long pilose apically; metatibia broad, laterally compressed and densely long-haired, hairs on dorsal surface longer than width of tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D462A449AA4A" blockId="4.[189,1399,574,636]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ABDOMEN. Black and rather long black pilose; terga II and III each with one pair of large rectangular yellowish-brown maculae; pregenital terga black pilose.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D4FFA436AA8C" blockId="4.[189,816,675,701]" box="[189,816,675,701]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
GENITALIA (
<figureCitation id="CBE687FCFF98FFB4FE92D4FFA689AA8C" box="[328,399,675,701]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1879,1905]" captionTargetBox="[238,1369,923,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1401,893,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Trichopsomyia pilosa sp. nov., male genitalia, holotype (NHMUK 010864268). A. Lateral view. B. Epandrium, dorsal view. C. Apical part of hypandrium, ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954992" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954992/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). See under diagnosis and remarks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF30D4B9A643AACE" blockId="4.[189,325,741,802]" box="[234,325,741,767]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FF30D4B9A643AACE" bold="true" box="[234,325,741,767]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D554A63FAB13" blockId="4.[189,325,741,802]" box="[189,313,776,802]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="07A2CBF1FF98FFB4FF67D10BA203AFA5" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954992" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3954992" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954992/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" startId="4.[189,232,1879,1905]" targetBox="[238,1369,923,1815]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="53629B79FF98FFB4FF67D10BA203AFA5" blockId="4.[189,1399,1879,1941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FF67D10BA60CAF40" bold="true" box="[189,266,1879,1905]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="94DDE0FAFF98FFB4FECBD10BA509AF40" authority="Steenis &amp; Wyatt, 2020" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Wyatt" authorityYear="2020" box="[273,527,1879,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Trichopsomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FECBD10BA509AF40" box="[273,527,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Trichopsomyia pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="7A9AFA10FF98FFB4FDCFD10BA574AF40" box="[533,626,1879,1905]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male genitalia, holotype (NHMUK 010864268). 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FB60D10BA3C9AF40" bold="true" box="[1210,1231,1879,1905]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">A</emphasis>
. Lateral view. 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FF67D126A7D7AFA5" bold="true" box="[189,209,1914,1940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">B</emphasis>
. Epandrium, dorsal view. 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF98FFB4FDDFD126A51CAFA5" bold="true" box="[517,538,1914,1940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">C</emphasis>
. Apical part of hypandrium, ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="1BC7C8F2FF99FFB5FF67D757A69CAABC" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="53629B79FF99FFB5FF67D757A629A914" blockId="5.[189,303,267,293]" box="[189,303,267,293]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<heading id="082A2C15FF99FFB5FF67D757A629A914" bold="true" box="[189,303,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" reason="3">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF99FFB5FF67D757A629A914" bold="true" box="[189,303,267,293]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53629B79FF99FFB5FF67D765A69CAABC" blockId="5.[189,1399,313,653]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
According to the description and figures in 
<bibRefCitation id="374CE688FF99FFB5FD6CD766A4A9A962" author="Downes M. F. &amp; Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C." box="[694,943,313,340]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Downes" journalOrPublisher="Australian Entomologist" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="29 - 38" part="44" refId="ref4903" refString="Downes M. F., Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C. 2017. A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia. Australian Entomologist 44 (1): 29 - 38." title="A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia" type="journal article" year="2017">
Downes 
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF99FFB5FCC7D766A451A962" box="[797,855,313,339]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
, our species is similar to the Australian 
<taxonomicName id="94DDE0FAFF99FFB5FF67D700A4F5A947" authority="Downes, Skevington &amp; Thompson, 2017" authorityName="Downes, Skevington &amp; Thompson" authorityYear="2017" box="[189,1011,348,374]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Trichopsomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formiciphila">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF99FFB5FF67D700A503A947" box="[189,517,348,374]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Trichopsomyia formiciphila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="374CE688FF99FFB5FDD7D700A4F5A947" author="Downes M. F. &amp; Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C." box="[525,1011,348,374]" firstAuthor="Downes" journalOrPublisher="Australian Entomologist" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="29 - 38" part="44" refId="ref4903" refString="Downes M. F., Skevington J. H. &amp; Thompson F. C. 2017. A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia. Australian Entomologist 44 (1): 29 - 38." title="A new ant inquiline flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae: Pipizinae) from Australia" type="journal article" year="2017">Downes, Skevington &amp; Thompson, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
based on the overall appearance of the species and especially the extent of pilosity on the katepisternum, the shape of the metasternum, the colour of the legs and abdomen, the long basoflagellomere and the infuscated wing with wide cell c. 
<taxonomicName id="94DDE0FAFF99FFB5FF67D798A6BAA9EF" authority="Steenis &amp; Wyatt, 2020" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Wyatt" authorityYear="2020" box="[189,444,452,478]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Trichopsomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="61A9476BFF99FFB5FF67D798A6BAA9EF" box="[189,444,452,478]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Trichopsomyia pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="7A9AFA10FF99FFB5FE1ED798A526A9EF" box="[452,544,452,478]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
